.TH "SANITIZER.REPLACEELEMENTWITHCHILDREN" "3JS" "January 16, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Sanitizer.replaceElementWithChildren \- Sanitizer:
replaceElementWithChildren() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]replaceElementWithChildren()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] interface sets an element to be replaced by its
child HTML elements when the sanitizer is used.
This is primarily used for stripping styles from text.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
replaceElementWithChildren(element)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]element\f[R]
A string indicating the name of the element to be replaced, or an object
with the following properties:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the element.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the element.
The default namespace is
\f[CR]\(dqhttp://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\(dq\f[R].
.RE
.SS Return value
\f[CR]true\f[R] if the operation changed the configuration to set the
element to be replaced by its children, and \f[CR]false\f[R] if the
sanitizer was already replacing the element.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic usage
This example shows the basic usage of the method, configuring a
sanitizer that replaces the \f[CR]<em>\f[R] element in inputs with its
child content.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Create sanitizer (in this case the default)\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer();

\f[I]// Replace <em> elements with their innerHTML\f[R]
sanitizer.replaceElementWithChildren(\(dqem\(dq);
.EE
.SS How to strip styles from text
This example shows how \f[CR]replaceElementWithChildren()\f[R] can be
used to strip styles from text.
.SS JavaScript
The code first creates a new \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] object that initially
allows \f[CR]<p>\f[R], \f[CR]<em>\f[R], and \f[CR]<strong>\f[R]
elements.
We then call \f[CR]replaceElementWithChildren()\f[R] on the sanitizer
specifying that \f[CR]<strong>\f[R] elements should be replaced.
.PP
The code defines a string that has \f[CR]<strong>\f[R] elements and uses
\f[CR]Element.setHTML()\f[R] with the sanitizer to inject the string.
The original string, the sanitized HTML from the element, and the
sanitizer are logged.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Create sanitizer using SanitizerConfig\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  elements: [\(dqp\(dq, \(dqem\(dq, \(dqstrong\(dq],
});

\f[I]// Replace the <strong> element\f[R]
sanitizer.replaceElementWithChildren(\(dqstrong\(dq);

\f[B]const\f[R] unsanitizedString = \(ga<p>This is a with <strong>important</strong> text <em>highlighted</em>.</p>\(ga;
log(\(gaunsanitizedHTMLString:\(rsn ${unsanitizedString}\(ga);

\f[I]// Create a <div> element\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] divElement = document.createElement(\(dqdiv\(dq);

divElement.setHTML(unsanitizedString, { sanitizer });
log(\(ga\(rsn\(rsnsanitizedHTML:\(rsn ${divElement.innerHTML}\(ga);

\f[I]// Log the sanitizer configuration\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizerConfig = sanitizer.get();
log(\(ga\(rsn\(rsnsanitizerConfig:\(rsn ${JSON.stringify(sanitizerConfig, \f[B]null\f[R], 2)}\(ga);
.EE
.SS Results
The original unsanitized HTML string, the sanitized string from the
element, and the sanitizer are logged below.
Note that the \f[CR]<strong>\f[R] styling is stripped from the text, but
the \f[CR]<em>\f[R] element is not.
Note also that the \f[CR]<strong>\f[R] element was originally in the
\f[CR]elements\f[R] list in the configuration, but was removed when it
was added to the \f[CR]replaceWithChildrenElements\f[R] list.
